\"2014-08-08 15:08:25\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-08-08 15:08:25\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:85:\"[simply_instagram endpoints=\"users\" type=\"recent-media\" size=\"thumbnail\" display=\"1\"]\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:13:\"Photo Gallery\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:13:\"photo-gallery\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2014-08-08 15:22:54\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-08-08 15:22:54\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1077\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:25;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1130;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2014-09-15 17:37:19\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-15 17:37:19\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:12724:\"Last year\'s schedule will give you an idea of the types of workshops and speakers we plan for the weekend. This year\'s schedule should be up soon.\r\n<table id=\"tcwtable\" border=\"5\" width=\"100%\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"150\" scope=\"column\" bgcolor=\"#012869\">\r\n<h3><span style=\"color: white;\"><strong>Friday, September 20, 2013</strong></span></h3>\r\n</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" width=\"14.4%\">7:30 - 8:30</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Buffet Style Breakfast</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" scope=\"row\">8:30 - 9:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\"><strong>Welcome and Opening Remarks</strong>\r\n<em>Dr. Robert E. Cummings, Founding Director of the Center for Writing and Rhetoric</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" scope=\"row\">8:45 - 9:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\"><strong>Video Vignettes and TCW Documentary Project</strong>\r\n<em>Introduced by Briana McCoy and Andrew Davis</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">9:00 - 10:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"42.8%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A and 404B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"42.8%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405A and 405B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Starting a Secondary School Writing Center</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Pamela Childers, Writing Scholar</em>\r\n(Session 1 of 2) This workshop will focus on helping participants determine how a writing center might func-tion in their school. By pre-senting some models, then allowing teachers to consid-er what they see as the goal of a writing center at their institutions, attendees will then begin a strategic plan.</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Introducing Evidence-Based Writing in the Composition Classroom</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Mary Ann Parker</em>\r\nDiscuss strategies that enable students to writing using text-based evidence while meeting the CCSS standards.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">10:00 - 10:50</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Keynote Session: Writing Across the Curriculum Partnerships</strong>\r\n<em>Pamela Childers</em>\r\n(Part 1) What is WAC? How does it impact what we teach and how we teach writing in our classes in secondary school, community college, and university classrooms? This session will focus on these questions and others related to helping our students make transitions vertically (from secondary to postsecondary to career) and horizontally (within classes across disciplines). The presentation will be followed by roundtable discussions with teachers of writing in various disciplines.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" scope=\"row\">10:50 - 11:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\"><strong>Break:</strong> Sponsored by Cengage</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">11:00 - Noon</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A and 404B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405A and 405B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Disciplinary Roundtables</strong>\r\n<em>With representatives of different disciplines, majors, and units at Ole Miss.</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Using ePortfolios in the Writing Classroom (Workshop)</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Andrew Davis and Ruth Mirtz</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Teaching Analysis (Workshop)</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Sheena Boran and Kerry Bowers</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" scope=\"row\">Noon - 1:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Lunch:</strong> Sponsored by TYCAM\r\nParticipation Opportunity: TCW Documentary Project</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">1:00 - 2:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\"><strong>Keynote Session: Reality vs. Mythology: Teaching English in the Two-Year College</strong>\r\n<em>Laura Hammons</em>Much confusion about the differences between teaching English on the high school, community college, and senior college levels exists within our profession. The myths and realities of being a community college teacher will be explored. The differences in the political structures of all three levels and their impact on teachers and students will lead into a discussion of possible remedies and a retelling of some war stories. Emphasis will be improving the learning experience for students.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"row\">2:00 - 3:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Catalpha</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Developing a Secondary School Writing Center</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Pamela Childers</em>\r\nBuilding on the morning workshop, participants will craft a strategic plan for developing a writing center with the assistance of nearby postsecondary writing centers.</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Strategies for Engaging Student Writers</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Laura Hammons and Kathi Griffin</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Writing in Online Spaces and Technology in the Writing Classroom</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Karen Leffler, Brittany Moore, and Andrew Davis</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Developing Cross-Curriculuar Writing Assignments</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Angela Green and Jo Fordham</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"row\">3:00 - 3:30</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Catalpa</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A and 404B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Peer Review Workshop</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Paula Miller and Briana McCoy</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Building a Community in the Writing Classroom</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Keith Boran, Victoria Bryan, and Anna Britt-Begnaud</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405A and 405B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Teaching Primary and Secondary Research Processes</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Karla Lyles and Mike Schwartz</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"45\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Deep Reading/Better Writing</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Brittany Moore and Jason Jones</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">4:30 - 5:30</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"90\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Welcome Reception:</strong> Sponsored by the Division of Outreach and the University of Mississippi Writing Project</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"15\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">5:30 - 7:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A and 404B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Library 106E</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Writing Teachers Writing: Designing and Using Collaborative Writing Assignments</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Alice Myatt and Karla Lyles</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Re-Designing First-Year Writing Courses: Writing 100/101 at the University of Mississippi</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Guy Krueger and Karen Forgette</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"30\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Multimodality: What It Is and How to Teach It</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Andrew Davis and Paula Miller</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table id=\"tcwtable\" border=\"5\" width=\"100%\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"24\" scope=\"column\" bgcolor=\"#012869\">\r\n<h3><span style=\"color: white;\"><strong>Saturday, September 21, 2013</strong></span></h3>\r\n</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\" width=\"14.4%\">7:30 - 8:30</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Buffet Style Breakfast</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">8:30 - 9:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\"><strong>Welcome</strong>\r\n<em>Alice Myatt, TCW Program Coordinator</em><strong>Opening Remarks</strong>\r\n<em>Rosemary Oliphant-Ingham, School of Education, Univ. of Mississippi</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\"><strong>Video Vignettes &amp; TCW Documentary Project</strong>\r\n<em>Introduced by Briana McCoy and Andrew Davis</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">9:00 - 10:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A and 404B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405A and 405B</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"28.53%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Catalpha</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Peer Review Workshop</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Paula Miller and Briana McCoy</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Introducing Evidence-Based Writing in the Composition Classroom</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Mary Ann Parker</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"6\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Science Writing Workshop</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Jo Fordham</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">10:00 - 11:00</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"9\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"42.8%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>404A</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"9\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\" width=\"42.8%\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>405A</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"9\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Landscape of Community College Writing</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Anna Britt-Begnaud and Laura Hammons</em></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"9\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Landscape of High School Writing</strong>\r\n<em>Facilitated by Kimber Woelfel and Jason Jones</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">11:00 - Noon</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\"><strong>Keynote Session: Writing Across the Curriculum Partnerships</strong>\r\n<em>Pamela Childers</em>\r\n(Part Two)- How does WAC impact what we know and how we will teach writing in the future to meet the Common Core Standards? What kind of partnerships are already occurring? How can we prepare current and future teachers to work collaboratively with colleagues in other disciplines and at other academic levels? This plenary will build upon the Friday plenary and focus more on faculty development.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<th colspan=\"6\" rowspan=\"2\" scope=\"row\">Noon - 1:30</th>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\" bgcolor=\"#F0F0F0\">\r\n<h3 align=\"center\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></h3>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"18\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Lunch\r\nWriting Across the Curriculum Partnerships: Presenting and Sharing Collaborative Writing Assignments and Multimodal Assignments</strong>\r\nAttendees, if you have multimodal or collaborative writing assignments, please bring them with you so that you may share or receive feedback on them.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<blockquote><em>The Transitioning to College Writing Symposium was made possible in part by a grant from The Mississippi Humanities Council. The Mississippi Humanities Council is an independent, nonpartisan, nonpolitical organization funded by the National Endowment for the Humanities and private donations. The Council’s primary objective is to shed light, not heat, on the public policy issues of today by examining the larger value questions involved through the use of philosophy, literature, history, and other disciplines in the humanities. </em></blockquote>\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:7:\"Program\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:7:\"program\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:26:47\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:26:47\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1126;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1130\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:26;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1154;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2014-09-16 15:58:40\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-16 15:58:40\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:11368:\"&nbsp;\r\n<table id=\"table-3\" border=\"5\" width=\"100%\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-1\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"5\"><strong>Friday, September 28, 2012</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>7:30-8:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Buffet Style Breakfast</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>8:30-9:00</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Welcome</strong>\r\nDr. Robert E. Cummings, Director of the Center for Writing and Rhetoric</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Opening Remarks</strong>\r\nDr. Andy Mullins, Chief of Staff to the Chancellor, and Associate Professor of Leadership &amp; Counselor Education and Co-Director of Mississippi Teacher Corps</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>9:00-9:15</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Video Vignettes</strong> of writing teachers, writing students, writing tutors and directors- presenting schools, teachers, and student from high schools, 2- and 4-year colleges, and writing centers</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>9:15-10:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" width=\"40%\"><em>405 A &amp; B</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" width=\"40%\"><em>404 A &amp; B</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IA</strong>\r\n“Standards to Teach By: The Common Core &amp; the Framework for Success in Postsecondary Writing Standards and How They Affect Teaching Writing at All Levels”- Dr. Ellen Shelton with Tara Gilstrap (University of Mississippi) and Mary Ann Parker (DeSoto Central High School)</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IB</strong>\r\n“Building Bridges for Transition: Supporting Writing Classrooms with Writing Centers” (A Resource Tool Kit)- Amber Jensen, Writing Center Sponsor (Edison High School) and Anna Britt-Begnaud, Writing Center Director (Itawamba Community College). Includes question and answer session.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>10:00-10:15</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Introduction of Cluster Meeting Strategies- a how to session with handouts and Morning Break</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>10:15-11:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>403, 404A, 404B, 405A, 405B, Catalpha, 412</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session I:</strong> In small groups, attendees will explore and discuss current topics, and then select one for which the group will develop (in session 2) interventions, strategies, and resources for sharing with Saturday’s attendees.  Guidelines will be distributed.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>11:00-11:55</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IIA</strong>Part 1 (11:00 - 11:25)\r\n\"It’s All About Location: Reflections on Student Preparedness and the Transfer of Knowledge\"\r\nDr. Chris Anson</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IIB</strong>Part 2 (11:25 - 11:55)\r\nTeaching Writing in the 21st Century: Question and Answer Open Session with Dr. Chris Anson</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Noon-1:00</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Lunch</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"4\"><strong>1:00-2:15</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>403</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Catalpha</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop\r\n</strong>Teaching Grammar in the Context of Student Writing\r\nFacilitated by Ellen Shelton &amp; Anna Britt-Begnaud</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop</strong>\r\nBeyond the MLA: Strategies for teaching style guide use\r\nFacilitated by Alice Myatt &amp; Ruth Mirtz</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>405A</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>404A</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop\r\n</strong>Identifying the role of technology in the composition classroom\r\nFacilitated by Mike Schwartz, Kathleen Turner &amp; Andrew Davis</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop</strong>\r\nIntegrating peer response in the writing classroom\r\nFacilitated by Paula Miller &amp; Amber Jensen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>2:15-3:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>403, 404A, 404B, 405A, 405B, Catalpha, 412</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session II:</strong> Building on Cluster Session I, groups will continue strategizing, intervening, and sharing resources .</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>3:30-3:45</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session Recap:</strong> Each group will select a presenter who will deliver the results of the cluster session to the attendees from 11:00-Noon on Saturday. Presentations may be made via the Internet (Transitioning website), PowerPoint, Prezi, handouts, giant poster-pad notes, or a combination of the preceding. Resources, including laptops and access to a printer, will be made available as needed. Contact Andrew Davis or Joanne Mitchell to arrange for access to resources.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>3:45-4:00</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Break: Prep for Tours</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>4:00-5:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Walk of Champions</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>J.D Williams Library</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 1</strong>\r\nDouble Decker Bus Tour of UM campus and Oxford with Dr. Andy Mullins</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 2\r\n</strong>Writing Center - Main Campus with Alice Myatt</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 3\r\n</strong>Archives and Special Collections with Leigh McWhite</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>5:15-6:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Ole Miss Oxford Depot</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Viewing at the Depot\r\n</strong>Reception with snacks and sodas provided.\r\nWriting Assessment and Responding to Student Writing: View and Discuss the videos <em>Beyond the Red Ink</em> and <em>Writing Across Borders</em>.\r\nFacilitated by Sheena Boran &amp; Kathleen Turner</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<table id=\"table-3\" border=\"5\" width=\"100%\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-1\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"5\"><strong>Saturday, September 29, 2012</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>7:30-8:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Buffet Style Breakfast</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>8:30-8:45</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Welcome\r\n</strong>Dr. Ellen Shelton, National Writing Project</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Opening Remarks</strong>\r\nDr. Stephen Monroe, Associate Dean, College of Liberal Arts</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>8:45-9:30</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"><strong>Plenary Session IIIA\r\n</strong>“Standards to Teach By: The Common Core &amp; the Framework for Success in Postsecondary Writing Standards and How They Affect Teaching Writing at All Levels”- Dr. Ellen Shelton with Karen Forgette (University of Mississippi)</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"><strong>Plenary Session IIIB\r\n</strong>“Building Bridges for Transition: Supporting Writing Classrooms with Writing Centers” (A Resource Tool Kit)- Dr. Kerri Jordan, Mississippi College, and Amber Jensen, Edison High School. Followed by a question and answer session.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>9:30-9:45</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Break</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"4\"><strong>9:45-11:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room A\r\n</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room B\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion</strong>\r\nClosing the divide between expectation and reality in the writing classroom\r\nFacilitated by Guy Krueger &amp; Sheena Boran</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion\r\n</strong>Writing in the Disciplines: Strategies for the writing classroom, Presentation by Angela Green\r\nFacilitated by Andrew Davis and Alice Myatt</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room C\r\n</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion\r\n</strong>Dual-enrollment courses and first-year composition\r\nFacilitated by Deborah Kehoe, Anna Britt-Begnaud, Victoria Bryan, &amp; Robert Cummings</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion</strong>\r\nIntegrating peer response into the writing classroom and writing center\r\nFacilitated by Keith Boran, Paula Miller &amp; Amber Jensen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>11:00-Noon</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Group Presentations of Interventions:</strong>\r\nA representative from each cluster will deliver a presentation based on their group work</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Noon-1:30</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\"><strong>Lunch and Closing Session\r\nViewing of selected <em>Take 20</em> clips\r\nPlanning for 2013 - </strong>announcements and dates to save</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:7:\"Program\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:7:\"program\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:28:07\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:28:07\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1151;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1154\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:27;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1273;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:43:32\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:43:32\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:92:\"[gview file=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Program_FINAL.pdf\"]\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:7:\"Program\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:7:\"program\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:43:43\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-09-23 16:43:43\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1271;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1273\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:28;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1415;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:24:54\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:24:54\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:113:\"[gview file=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-Transitioning-Schedule-Sheet1.pdf\"]\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:7:\"Program\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:7:\"program\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-10-02 14:41:30\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-10-02 14:41:30\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1410;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1415\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:29;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:77;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 19:10:38\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 19:10:38\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2513:\"Please complete the form below to register for the Transitioning to College Writing Symposium. When you have submitted your registration information, you will receive a confirmation email. Please print this email for your records. <strong>Note</strong>: <strong>Online Registration Deadline: Monday, September 28, 2015</strong>. After that date, registrations will be taken via phone (662.915.2121) or email (<a title=\"email for transitioning registration\" href=\"mailto:transitioning@olemiss.edu\" target=\"_blank\">transitioning@olemiss.edu</a>).\r\n\r\n<strong>Registration Fee - $30</strong>\r\nTo pay with credit or debit through PayPal, please follow the link at the bottom of this page after you submit the registration form.\r\n\r\nIf paying by check, please send payment to: \r\n\r\nDept. of Writing and Rhetoric\r\nAttn: Joanne Mitchell\r\nP.O. Box 1848\r\nLamar Hall, 3rd Floor, Suite B\r\nUniversity, MS 38655\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: May I pay with a PO (Purchase Order)? </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>A: Yes.</strong> Here\'s how: Register as if you were sending in a check. Then, send an email to <a title=\"email registration information\" href=\"mailto:transitioning@olemiss.edu\" target=\"_blank\">transitioning@olemiss.edu</a> with your purchase order information and contact information. We will issue an invoice to the address you provide, referencing the purchase order; once we receive payment, a receipt will be sent to the address/contact you provide.\r\n\r\nTo pay with credit, debit, or PayPal, please follow the link at the bottom of this page after you submit the registration form.\r\n\r\nAfter registering, you will be added to the Transitioning listserv so that we can send you alerts and announcements via email. If you do not want to be added to the listserv, send an email to <a href=\"mailto:transitioning@olemiss.edu\">transitioning@olemiss.edu.</a>\r\n\r\nIf you have any questions about this form, please contact us at <a href=\"mailto:transitioning@olemiss.edu\">transitioning@olemiss.edu</a> or (662) 915-2121.\r\n\r\n[contact-form-7 id=\"80\" title=\"Registration Form\"]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>About PayPal Registration</h3>\r\nIf you would like to pay for your Transitioning to College Writing Symposium registration using a credit or debit card, please enter your name below and select a registration type <strong>after</strong> submitting your registration above. Since we process credit and debit cards using PayPal, we need you to enter your name and registration type a second time so we can confirm your payment.\r\n\r\n[wp_paypal_payment]\r\n\r\n<hr />\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:12:\"Registration\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:12:\"registration\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-06-12 18:32:40\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-06-12 18:32:40\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:44:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=77\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:30;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:989;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2013-09-26 15:04:44\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2013-09-26 15:04:44\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1482:\"<h2>Transitioning Assignment Showcase</h2>\r\nThe Transitioning to College Writing Symposium needs you to share your wisdom! We work to collect assignments, activities, readings, or any other documents related to the teaching of writing that you are willing to share with others teachers. You can upload a resource to us directly on this page. Just give us your name, school, and a description of the file you\'re uploading, and we\'ll put it on this page.\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>UM Writing 100/101</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=2 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n<h3>UM Writing 102</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=3 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n<h3>UM LIBA 102</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=4 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n<h3>UM Writing 250</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=5 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n<h3>UM Minor in Professional Writing</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=6 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n<h3>High School &amp; Community College Assignments</h3>\r\n[wpfilebase tag=list id=7 tpl=table pagenav=1 /]\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h2>Share a Resource</h2>\r\n[wordpress_file_upload uploadpath=\"uploads/resources\" uploadrole=\"all\" subfoldertree=\"*resources/resources\" dublicatespolicy=\"maintain both\" uniquepattern=\"datetimestamp\" placements=\"subfolders/userdata/selectbutton+filename/uploadbutton\" uploadtitle=\"Share Resources\" widths=\"userdata:200px, userdata_label:200px, userdata_value:200px\" heights=\"uploadfolder_label:50px, userdata:50px\" userdata=\"true\" userdatalabel=\"*Name/*School/*Description of Resource \" medialink=\"true\"]\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:9:\"Resources\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:9:\"resources\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-09-30 21:25:06\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-09-30 21:25:06\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:45:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=989\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:31;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:2;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2014-07-31 19:31:14\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-07-31 19:31:14\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:968:\"This is an example page. It\'s different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:\n\n<blockquote>Hi there! I\'m a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my blog. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like pi&#241;a coladas. (And gettin\' caught in the rain.)</blockquote>\n\n...or something like this:\n\n<blockquote>The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.</blockquote>\n\nAs a new WordPress user, you should go to <a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-admin/\">your dashboard</a> to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:11:\"Sample Page\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:4:\"open\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:11:\"sample-page\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2014-07-31 19:31:14\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-07-31 19:31:14\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:45:\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/?page_id=2\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:32;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1424;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:36:04\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:36:04\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:7479:\"<h3>Ms. Anna Britt Begnaud</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DSC00210.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-594 size-thumbnail\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DSC00210-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Anna Brit-Begnaud \" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Anna Britt Begnaud is Writing Center Director and English Instructor at Itawamba Community College in Fulton and Tupelo, Mississippi. Her MA in English has a concentration in Composition and Rhetoric from the University of Alabama, and she serves on the executive board of the Mississippi Writing Centers Association. Her work incorporates her research and interest in the uses of New Media in the Composition Classroom, Visual and Digital Rhetorics, and Working with the Net Generation in composition classrooms. Her presentation, \"Write Here; Write Now: Quality Enhancement Plans Can Be Good!\", will draw on her recent work as Coordinator of a writing center focused Quality Enhancement Plan at ICC.\r\n<h3>Dr. Robert E. Cummings</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/2014_faculty_9.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1201\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/2014_faculty_9.jpg\" alt=\"Robert Cummings\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Robert Cummings serves as Chair of the Department of Writing and Rhetoric and Associate Professor of English at the University of Mississippi. In 2006 he earned the PhD in English from the University of Georgia, with a focus on the connections between rhetoric, composition, and digital technology. His first book was the co-edited volume Wiki Writing: Collaborative Learning in the College Classroom with Matt Barton, (U of Michigan P digitalculturebooks: 2008). In the following year he authored <em>Lazy Virtues: Teaching Writing in the Age of Wikipedia</em> (Vanderbilt UP, 2009), which won the 2009 MLA Mina Shaughnessy award. More recently he has won grants to promote Open Educational Resources and online composition. Similarly, he has served Wikipedia community, Wikimedia Foundation, and Wiki Ed Foundation as a frequent consultant on matters pertaining to higher education. His recent projects have included a Fulbright Specialist Award to support teaching with Wikipedia at University of Sydney, and research on the rhetoric of fear, uncertainty, and doubt. Along with Anna Britt-Begnaud, Dr. Cummings\'s presentation is titled \"Write Here; Write Now: Quality Enhancement Plans Can Be Good!\"\r\n<h3>Dr. Frances Di Lauro</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/resource.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1202\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/resource.jpg\" alt=\"Frances Di Lauro \" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Dr. Frances Di Lauro<strong> </strong>is a Lecturer and Coordinator of the Student Writing Fellows Program at the Writing Hub, where she teaches writing and rhetoric. Frances serves as eLearning representative, and is the Academic Integrity Coordinator for the Faculty of Arts and Social Sciences at the University of Sydney, Australia. Her research interest on the rhetorical features of communication extends to texts relating to food, educational films, advertisements, documentaries, and propaganda films. She incorporates active learning experiences for students by incorporating Wikipedia editing in the courses she coordinates. Frances will speak on “Teaching research and writing across the curriculum at the University of Sydney” and “Writing across Borders in a Digital Age” while here at the Symposium.\r\n<h3><strong>Ms. Amber Jensen</strong></h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/photo.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1331 size-full\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/photo.jpg\" alt=\"Amber Jensen \" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Amber Jenson is a National Board Certified high school English teacher, the founding director of the Edison High School Writing Center, and a Ph.D student in Writing and Rhetoric at George Mason University. She serves as the Secondary Schools Representative on the International Writing Centers Association Executive Board, and is currently developing a regional high school writing centers association called Capital Area Peer Tutors Association (CAPTA). Amber will be a Symposium Workshop Leader, which will be \"Training Tomorrow’s Tutors Today\". During her workshop, Amber will draw on research she has done as she works on one of her latest papers, which as its focus training tutors for work in online tutoring spaces.\r\n<h3><strong>Dr. Lawrence T. Potter, Jr.</strong></h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DeanPotter.png\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1203\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/DeanPotter.png\" alt=\"Lawrence Potter\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Dr. Lawrence T. Potter, Jr., served as Dean of the College of Liberal Arts at Jackson State University from 2012 until June 2014. Currently, Potter is a tenured professor in the Department of English and co-directs the M.A. in English. Dr. Potter has been a successful university administrator and tenured professor for more than seventeen years. Potter came to Jackson State University from a dual appointment at DePaul University in Chicago and Allegheny College in Meadville, Pennsylvania. At DePaul, Potter was special assistant for faculty development and diversity since 2012; and, at Allegheny he was associate dean of the College, chief diversity officer and professor of English at Allegheny College and a member of the President’s Senior Staff since 2010. Dr. Potter is a charter member of the National Association of Diversity Officers in Higher Education (NADOHE), serves on the Board of Directors for select non-profits in Chicago and Pittsburgh, and he is an active with several academic and professional organizations. Potter graduated magna cum laude with a triple major in English, philosophy, and religion from Stillman College. Dr. Potter will deliver the Symposium’s Keynote address on Friday, October 10, at 1 pm. His address, titled \"The Write Stuff: How Inclusive Practices, Intentional Support and Purposeful Planning Yield Student Success,\" emphasizes the value of writing in student retention and success.\r\n<h3><strong>Mr. Vincent Segalini</strong></h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_2343-800x600-3.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1339 size-full\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_2343-800x600-3.jpg\" alt=\"Vincent Segalini \" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Vincent Segalini is Director of English Language Arts with the Mississippi Department of Education. Vincent Segalini currently serves as the director of English and language arts for the Mississippi Department of Education. Vincent has 14 years of classroom experience in all grade levels and various subject areas. He most recently taught English II in Simpson County. At the 2013 Making Connections Conference in Biloxi, Mississippi, Segalini led workshops on the ELA Common Core State Standards, the PARCC Assessment for ELA, the Close Reading of the English Language Arts CCSS and Determining Text Complexity. Mr. Segalini will give his presentation on \"Transitioning with Writing and the Common Core State Standards\".\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:8:\"Speakers\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:8:\"speakers\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:36:30\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:36:30\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1410;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1424\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:33;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1055;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2014-08-04 16:32:17\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2014-08-04 16:32:17\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:2020:\"<h2>METP Breakfast with Dr. Cynthia Selfe</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/metp_logo.png\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1488\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/metp_logo.png\" alt=\"METP Logo \" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>The Mississippi Excellence in Teaching Program at UM will sponsor Friday morning\'s breakfast with Dr. Cyndi Selfe. Dr. Selfe will speak about the role of oral histories, digital literacy narratives, and how to integrate digital literacy in local communities, high schools, and college &amp; universities.\r\n\r\nAlso, students from the METP program at UM, along with faculty and staff, will share their experiences and answer questions. For more about METP, visit their <a href=\"http://metp.olemiss.edu\" target=\"_blank\">website</a>.\r\n<h2>Digital Archive of Literacy Narratives Collection Event</h2>\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-1690\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/header-300x75.jpg\" alt=\"DALN Logo\" width=\"300\" height=\"75\" /></a>The Digital Archive of Literacy Narratives, hosted through Ohio State University, is a \"publicly available archive of personal literacy narratives in a variety of formats (text, video, audio) that together provide a historical record of the literacy practices and values of contributors, as those practices and values change.\" At the 2015 Transitioning to College Writing Symposium, we invite you to submit your literacy narrative to the archive. Stations will be setup on Thursday night in Lamar Hall 206 (our Digital Humanities center) and in room #128 at the Jackson Avenue Center on Friday. You may record audio, video, or simply use the space to type out your literacy narrative. Release forms will be available, and we\'ll take care of the uploading for you.\r\n\r\nFor more information about the DALN, visit <a href=\"http://daln.osu.edu\">daln.osu.edu</a>.\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:14:\"Special Events\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:8:\"CONTENTS\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:13:\"specialevents\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-09-25 13:39:59\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-09-25 13:39:59\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:42:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/events-2/\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:34;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:1429;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"1\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:39:25\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:39:25\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:1829:\"We have two special events that we want to share with you. Read on for details.\r\n\r\n<h3>Friday Evening Reception</h3>\r\nOur reception opens Friday afternoon at 5:00 pm and continues until 8:00 pm. This will be an excellent opportunity to explore our new Writing Center, network with other teachers, to meet and talk with our visiting scholars, France di Lauro from the University of Sydney and Amber Jensen from Edison High School in Fairfax, Virginia.\r\n\r\nThe reception this year is a bit different: we will run concurrent sessions during the reception, where the food will be set up in our new Lamar Hall conference room. The conference room is across from our new Writing Center, which will be open during the reception time. So, grab a plate, take in a workshop (or two), and enjoy the company of our guests and attendees!\r\n\r\n<h3>Special Session of MCTE, the Mississippi Council of Teachers of English</h3>\r\nThis event takes place during lunch Saturday, 12:00 - 1:30 pm; lunch is a build-your-own taco or salad catered by South Depot Tacos courtesy of the UM School of Education. \r\n\r\nThe MCTE, which has a long and rich history as an affiliate of the NCTE, has for the past few years been a bit quiet. Now, under the leadership of Marilyn Schultz of Delta State University and Rosemary Oliphant Ingham of the University of Mississippi, the MCTE is once again gaining traction as an association to support English teachers throughout Mississippi.\r\n\r\nEveryone is invited to stay for lunch and learn more about the MCTE, its goals, and its plans for the upcoming year. English professors and instructors from Mississippi State, Jackson State, University of Southern Mississippi, Mississippi College, and Mississippi University for Women are also part of the reactivation of the MCTE and plan to be present at Saturday\'s luncheon.\r\n\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:14:\"Special Events\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:14:\"special-events\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:39:39\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-05-29 17:39:39\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:1410;s:4:\"guid\";s:46:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=1429\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:35;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:62;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 19:07:48\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 19:07:48\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:7144:\"<h3>DEPARTMENT OF WRITING AND RHETORIC</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://rhetoric.olemiss.edu\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-63\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/logo200px.gif\" alt=\"CWR Logo\" width=\"88\" height=\"100\" /></a>The Department of Writing and Rhetoric at the University of Mississippi was established in 2009 in response to a five-year Quality Enhancement Plan aimed at improving student writing in all disciplines. The department administers the University’s writing centers on the Oxford, DeSoto, and Tupelo campuses; it also directs composition courses for first-year students (WRIT 100, WRIT 101, WRIT 102, and LIBA 102) as well as WRIT 250 (formerly ENGL 250). W&amp;R supports the teaching of writing in all disciplines, and offers workshops on designing writing assignments and responding to student writing as a part of their Writing Across the Curriculum initiative.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://rhetoric.olemiss.edu\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>DIVISION OF OUTREACH</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-64\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/outreachbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Outreach Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"18\" /></a>The Division of Outreach and Continuing Education seeks to complement the mission and vision of the University through the breadth and diversity of the programs it offers the students at The University of Mississippi regardless of their campus-affiliation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>UNIVERSITY OF MISSISSIPPI WRITING PROJECT</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/writing_project\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-66\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/umwp-webbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Writing Project Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>The University of Mississippi Writing Project seeks to empower teachers to improve thinking, writing, teaching, and learning through access, diversity, and equity; through relevant and current teaching practices; and through teacher expertise, leadership, and reflection.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/writing_project/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>MISSISSIPPI EXCELLENCE IN TEACHING PROGRAM</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://metp.olemiss.edu\"><img class=\"aligncenter\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2014/08/metp_logo.png\" alt=\"METP Logo\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1488\" /></a>\r\nThe Mississippi Excellence in Teaching Program (METP) is a collaboration between the University of Mississippi (Ole Miss) and Mississippi State University (MSU) to attract top-performing students to an innovative new teacher education program using one of the most valuable scholarships ever offered in the state.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://metp.olemiss.edu\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr/> \r\n\r\n<h3>COLLEGE OF LIBERAL ARTS</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/libarts/\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-70\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LogoCLA.jpg\" alt=\"CLA logo\" width=\"86\" height=\"100\" /></a>The College of Liberal Arts provides the general education component of the University undergraduate degree programs, offers degree programs in liberal education to all of its own students, and extends the boundaries of scholarship in all of the varied disciplines associated with the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences. Its faculty seek not only to offer a sound curriculum but also to encourage the development of graduate study and to stimulate research, which is vital to good teaching and faculty growth. Liberal Arts faculty members participate actively in making the resources of the University useful to the general public and in shaping the cultural life of the institution.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/libarts/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n<h3>SCHOOL OF EDUCATION</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://education.olemiss.edu/\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-65\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/school-of-education.jpg\" alt=\"School of Ed Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>At The University Of Mississippi School of Education, undergraduate and graduate programs prepare candidates to be an inspiration to students, effective professional educators and advocates for diverse learners. Nationally and internationally renowned faculty who are successful authors and researchers serve as mentors throughout the candidate\'s teacher-preparation program.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://education.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENTER FOR EXCELLENCE IN TEACHING AND LEARNING</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/depts/cetl/\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-69\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CETL_web.jpg\" alt=\"CETL Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"36\" /></a>The Center for Excellence in Teaching and Learning was established in 2007 to promote student learning by continually improving teaching at The University of Mississippi. The Center works to provide resources and assistance to faculty members related to their teaching endeavors.\r\n\r\nRecognizing that learning is a process that needs constant attention and refinement, the Center works to promote an ongoing, university-wide discussion about teaching and learning issues. It is essential that faculty be engaged in dialogue about teaching and learning issues so that we can continue to adapt to the changing technology, student body, and understanding in our fields.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/depts/cetl/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>W.W. NORTON COMPANY</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://books.wwnorton.com/books/courselist.aspx?tid=578\"><img class=\"aligncenter wp-image-1117\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Norton001-300x132.jpg\" alt=\"WW Norton\" width=\"200\" height=\"88\" /></a>\r\n“Books are the weapons in the battle of ideas.” These were the words of William Warder Norton, who 90 years ago launched the firm that bears his name. Today, the three-person company he once ran from his living room has become the oldest and largest publishing house owned entirely by its employees.\r\n\r\n<a title=\"WWNorton English\" href=\"http://books.wwnorton.com/books/courselist.aspx?tid=578\" target=\"_blank\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>BEDFORD/ST.MARTIN\'S</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/default.aspx\"><img class=\"wp-image-1084 size-thumbnail aligncenter\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/MacEd_BSM_Logo1-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"Bedford Logo\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Bedford/St. Martin\'s began with composition in 1981, developing one book at a time to meet the way classrooms were changing. Today we have a lot more tools for English courses—in every shape, size, and medium—but the way we work remains the same. We build everything to meet the evolving needs of teachers and students, with deep development and informed innovation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/default.aspx\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\";s:10:\"post_title\";s:8:\"Sponsors\";s:12:\"post_excerpt\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_status\";s:7:\"publish\";s:14:\"comment_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:11:\"ping_status\";s:6:\"closed\";s:13:\"post_password\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"post_name\";s:8:\"sponsors\";s:7:\"to_ping\";s:0:\"\";s:6:\"pinged\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"post_modified\";s:19:\"2015-08-10 14:41:15\";s:17:\"post_modified_gmt\";s:19:\"2015-08-10 14:41:15\";s:21:\"post_content_filtered\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"post_parent\";i:0;s:4:\"guid\";s:44:\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/?page_id=62\";s:10:\"menu_order\";i:0;s:9:\"post_type\";s:4:\"page\";s:14:\"post_mime_type\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"comment_count\";s:1:\"0\";s:6:\"filter\";s:3:\"raw\";}i:36;O:7:\"WP_Post\":24:{s:2:\"ID\";i:48;s:11:\"post_author\";s:1:\"8\";s:9:\"post_date\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 18:50:54\";s:13:\"post_date_gmt\";s:19:\"2012-05-08 18:50:54\";s:12:\"post_content\";s:11266:\"<em><a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/2015-Transitioning-Schedule-Sheet11.pdf\">Download a PDF of the Program</a></em>\r\n<table id=\"tablepress-1\" class=\"tablepress tablepress-id-1\"><caption style=\"caption-side: bottom; text-align: left; border: none; background: none; margin: 0; padding: 0;\"> </caption>\r\n<thead>\r\n<tr class=\"row-1 odd\">\r\n<th class=\"column-1\" colspan=\"7\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Listen, Think, Respond: Engaging Students in Writing for Life</p>\r\n</th>\r\n</tr>\r\n</thead>\r\n<tbody class=\"row-hover\">\r\n<tr class=\"row-2 even\">\r\n<td class=\"column-1\" colspan=\"7\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Thursday, October 1, 2015, Lamar Hall</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr class=\"row-3 odd\">\r\n<td class=\"column-1\" rowspan=\"2\">6:00-6:30</td>\r\n<td class=\"column-2\" colspan=\"6\">Lamar Lobby</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr class=\"row-4 even\"