(1044, 1, '2014-09-15 17:18:35', '2014-09-15 17:18:35', '[responsive_vid]\n\n<hr />\n\nThe Mississippi Teachers Talk documentary project continues this year! We will have a place set up on both Friday and Saturday for teachers to talk about their teaching and their students. Teachers may engage with one or more of the following questions:\n\n<strong>Questions</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>How do you keep your writing instruction fresh from year to year?</li>\n	<li>How can we bring writing back to the forefront of the K-12 and college curriculum?</li>\n	<li>Are we, writing teachers, making a difference in our students\' lives?</li>\n	<li>Whose job is it to catch students who are struggling with writing and to struggle with them until they are able to succeed?</li>\n	<li>How do you foster student engagement with the revision process?</li>\n	<li>What has been your most successful strategy for peer review?</li>\n	<li>What strategies would you use to scaffold writing assignments for ESL students?</li>\n	<li>How has your approach to teaching writing evolved since your first experience?</li>\n	<li>What strategies do you use to help students revise and edit successfully?</li>\n	<li>How do you anticipate the expectations of each student\'s next academic level when making decisions about your curriculum?</li>\n	<li>How much do we do to promote Mississippi writers in our classrooms?</li>\n	<li>What, in your opinion, is the single most effective way to improve a student\'s writing?</li>\n	<li>How do you transition from the planning to the actual writing?</li>\n	<li>What is the very best writing assignment you ever gave your students, and what made it so effective?</li>\n	<li>In or outside of the classroom, what is the most challenging aspect of teaching writing for you?</li>\n	<li>Increasingly our students are predominantly kinesthetic learners. What are some practical strategies college writing teachers can use to keep these students engaged?</li>\n	<li>How do you explain to your students the difference between high school and college writing?</li>\n	<li>How do you teach your students the power of revision?</li>\n	<li>How do you get teachers in other disciplines to help students know the writing services your institution makes available?</li>\n	<li>What struggles or challenges do you see from high school seniors and Composi</li>\n</ul>', 'Documentary Project_2013', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '978-autosave-v1', '', '', '2014-09-15 17:18:35', '2014-09-15 17:18:35', '', 978, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/978-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1045, 1, '2014-08-01 21:50:24', '2014-08-01 21:50:24', '[responsive_vid]\r\n\r\n<hr/>\r\n\r\nWe hope you will participate in this documentary project! We are excited to hear what you have to say about teaching writing in Mississippi and the Memphis area.\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Please read and sign the release form before recording your responses.</li>\r\n	<li>Please identify yourself first, including your name and the name of the institution where you teach.</li>\r\n	<li>You may choose which questions to answer in your video response – do not feel obligated to answer them all, but focus on a few which you find particularly compelling, thought-provoking, or worth discussing.</li>\r\n	<li>We particularly would like variety in respondents - we’d love to have good representation from high schools, community colleges and four-year universities.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<strong>Questions</strong>\r\n\r\n1. Why do you teach writing?\r\n2. What do you think is the most challenging thing about teaching writing at your institution?\r\n3. What challenges/opportunities does the context of our teaching – in Mississippi and the Memphis area – present?\r\n4. What do you wish students knew before they set foot in your class for the first time?\r\n5. What advice would you give a new teacher who is about to begin their first semester of teaching writing at your institution?\r\n6. What do you wish teachers at other institutions (i.e., community colleges and four-year universities, if you are a high school teacher; high schools and four-year universities, if you are a community college teacher, etc.) knew about how you teach your students?', 'Documentary Project', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '978-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-01 21:50:24', '2014-08-01 21:50:24', '', 978, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/978-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1083, 1, '2014-08-08 15:41:44', '2014-08-08 15:41:44', '<h3>BEDFORD/ST.MARTIN\'S</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/bedford.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-67\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/bedford-300x208.jpg\" alt=\"Bedford Logo\" width=\"243\" height=\"169\" /></a>Bedford/St. Martin\'s began with composition in 1981, developing one book at a time to meet the way classrooms were changing. Today we have a lot more tools for English courses—in every shape, size, and medium—but the way we work remains the same. We build everything to meet the evolving needs of teachers and students, with deep development and informed innovation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/default.aspx\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENGAGE LEARNING</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/cengage.jpeg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-68\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/cengage.jpeg\" alt=\"Cengage Logo\" width=\"163\" height=\"63\" /></a>Cengage Learning is a leading provider of innovative teaching, learning and research solutions for the academic, professional and library markets worldwide. The company’s products and services are designed to foster academic excellence and professional development, increase student engagement, improve learning outcomes and deliver authoritative information to people whenever and wherever they need it.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.cengage.com/us/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENTER FOR EXCELLENCE IN TEACHING AND LEARNING</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CETL_web.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-69\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CETL_web.jpg\" alt=\"CETL Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"36\" /></a>The Center for Excellence in Teaching and Learning was established in 2007 to promote student learning by continually improving teaching at The University of Mississippi. The Center works to provide resources and assistance to faculty members related to their teaching endeavors.\r\n\r\nRecognizing that learning is a process that needs constant attention and refinement, the Center works to promote an ongoing, university-wide discussion about teaching and learning issues. It is essential that faculty be engaged in dialogue about teaching and learning issues so that we can continue to adapt to the changing technology, student body, and understanding in our fields.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/depts/cetl/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>DEPARTMENT OF WRITING AND RHETORIC</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/logo200px.gif\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-63\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/logo200px.gif\" alt=\"CWR Logo\" width=\"88\" height=\"100\" /></a>The Department of Writing and Rhetoric at the University of Mississippi was established in 2009 in response to a five-year Quality Enhancement Plan aimed at improving student writing in all disciplines. The department administers the University’s writing centers on the Oxford, DeSoto, and Tupelo campuses; it also directs composition courses for first-year students (WRIT 100, WRIT 101, WRIT 102, and LIBA 102) as well as WRIT 250 (formerly ENGL 250).  W&amp;R supports the teaching of writing in all disciplines, and offers workshops on designing writing assignments and responding to student writing as a part of their Writing Across the Curriculum initiative.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.cwr.olemiss.edu\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>COLLEGE OF LIBERAL ARTS</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LogoCLA.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-70\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LogoCLA.jpg\" alt=\"CLA logo\" width=\"86\" height=\"100\" /></a>The College of Liberal Arts provides the general education component of the University undergraduate degree programs, offers degree programs in liberal education to all of its own students, and extends the boundaries of scholarship in all of the varied disciplines associated with the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences. Its faculty seek not only to offer a sound curriculum but also to encourage the development of graduate study and to stimulate research, which is vital to good teaching and faculty growth. Liberal Arts faculty members participate actively in making the resources of the University useful to the general public and in shaping the cultural life of the institution.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/libarts/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>DIVISION OF OUTREACH</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/outreachbanner.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-64\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/outreachbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Outreach Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"18\" /></a>The Division of Outreach and Continuing Education seeks to complement the mission and vision of the University through the breadth and diversity of the programs it offers the students at The University of Mississippi regardless of their campus-affiliation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>SCHOOL OF EDUCATION</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/school-of-education.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-65\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/school-of-education.jpg\" alt=\"School of Ed Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>At The University Of Mississippi School of Education, undergraduate and graduate programs prepare candidates to be an inspiration to students, effective professional educators and advocates for diverse learners. Nationally and internationally renowned faculty who are successful authors and researchers serve as mentors throughout the candidate\'s teacher-preparation program.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://education.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>UNIVERSITY OF MISSISSIPPI WRITING PROJECT</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/umwp-webbanner.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-66\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/umwp-webbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Writing Project Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>The University of Mississippi Writing Project seeks to empower teachers to improve thinking, writing, teaching, and learning through access, diversity, and equity; through relevant and current teaching practices; and through teacher expertise, leadership, and reflection.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/writing_project/\">Visit Website</a>', 'Sponsors', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-08 15:41:44', '2014-08-08 15:41:44', '', 62, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/62-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1051, 1, '2014-08-04 14:15:52', '2014-08-04 14:15:52', '\r\n<h3>BEDFORD/ST.MARTIN\'S</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/bedford.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter  wp-image-67\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/bedford-300x208.jpg\" alt=\"Bedford Logo\" width=\"243\" height=\"169\" /></a>Bedford/St. Martin\'s began with composition in 1981, developing one book at a time to meet the way classrooms were changing. Today we have a lot more tools for English courses—in every shape, size, and medium—but the way we work remains the same. We build everything to meet the evolving needs of teachers and students, with deep development and informed innovation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/default.aspx\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENGAGE LEARNING</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/cengage.jpeg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-68\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/cengage.jpeg\" alt=\"Cengage Logo\" width=\"163\" height=\"63\" /></a>Cengage Learning is a leading provider of innovative teaching, learning and research solutions for the academic, professional and library markets worldwide. The company’s products and services are designed to foster academic excellence and professional development, increase student engagement, improve learning outcomes and deliver authoritative information to people whenever and wherever they need it.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.cengage.com/us/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENTER FOR EXCELLENCE IN TEACHING AND LEARNING</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CETL_web.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-69\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/CETL_web.jpg\" alt=\"CETL Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"36\" /></a>The Center for Excellence in Teaching and Learning was established in 2007 to promote student learning by continually improving teaching at The University of Mississippi. The Center works to provide resources and assistance to faculty members related to their teaching endeavors.\r\n\r\nRecognizing that learning is a process that needs constant attention and refinement, the Center works to promote an ongoing, university-wide discussion about teaching and learning issues. It is essential that faculty be engaged in dialogue about teaching and learning issues so that we can continue to adapt to the changing technology, student body, and understanding in our fields.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/depts/cetl/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>CENTER FOR WRITING AND RHETORIC</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/logo200px.gif\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-63\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/logo200px.gif\" alt=\"CWR Logo\" width=\"88\" height=\"100\" /></a>The Center for Writing and Rhetoric at the University of Mississippi was established in 2009 in response to a five-year Quality Enhancement Plan aimed at improving student writing in all disciplines. The CWR administers the University’s writing centers on the Oxford, DeSoto, and Tupelo campuses; it also directs composition courses for first-year students (WRIT 100, WRIT 101, WRIT 102, and LIBA 102) as well as WRIT 250 (formerly ENGL 250). The CWR operates as a separate academic unit with Dr. Robert Cummings as its director and with oversight from the dean of the Liberal Arts College. The CWR supports the teaching of writing in all disciplines, and offers workshops on designing writing assignments and responding to student writing as a part of their Writing Across the Curriculum initiative.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.cwr.olemiss.edu\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>COLLEGE OF LIBERAL ARTS</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LogoCLA.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-70\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/LogoCLA.jpg\" alt=\"CLA logo\" width=\"86\" height=\"100\" /></a>The College of Liberal Arts provides the general education component of the University undergraduate degree programs, offers degree programs in liberal education to all of its own students, and extends the boundaries of scholarship in all of the varied disciplines associated with the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences. Its faculty seek not only to offer a sound curriculum but also to encourage the development of graduate study and to stimulate research, which is vital to good teaching and faculty growth. Liberal Arts faculty members participate actively in making the resources of the University useful to the general public and in shaping the cultural life of the institution.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.olemiss.edu/libarts/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>DIVISION OF OUTREACH</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/outreachbanner.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-64\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/outreachbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Outreach Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"18\" /></a>The Division of Outreach and Continuing Education seeks to complement the mission and vision of the University through the breadth and diversity of the programs it offers the students at The University of Mississippi regardless of their campus-affiliation.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>SCHOOL OF EDUCATION</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/school-of-education.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-65\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/school-of-education.jpg\" alt=\"School of Ed Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>At The University Of Mississippi School of Education, undergraduate and graduate programs prepare candidates to be an inspiration to students, effective professional educators and advocates for diverse learners. Nationally and internationally renowned faculty who are successful authors and researchers serve as mentors throughout the candidate\'s teacher-preparation program.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://education.olemiss.edu/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n\r\n<h3>UNIVERSITY OF MISSISSIPPI WRITING PROJECT</h3>\r\n<a href=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/umwp-webbanner.jpg\"><img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-66\" src=\"http://130.74.44.156/transitioning/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/umwp-webbanner.jpg\" alt=\"Writing Project Logo\" width=\"220\" height=\"35\" /></a>The University of Mississippi Writing Project seeks to empower teachers to improve thinking, writing, teaching, and learning through access, diversity, and equity; through relevant and current teaching practices; and through teacher expertise, leadership, and reflection.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://www.outreach.olemiss.edu/writing_project/\">Visit Website</a>\r\n', 'Sponsors', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '62-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-08-04 14:15:52', '2014-08-04 14:15:52', '', 62, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/62-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
