ssippi) and Mary Ann Parker (DeSoto Central High School)</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IB</strong>\r\n“Building Bridges for Transition: Supporting Writing Classrooms with Writing Centers” (A Resource Tool Kit)- Amber Jensen, Writing Center Sponsor (Edison High School) and Anna Britt-Begnaud, Writing Center Director (Itawamba Community College). Includes question and answer session.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>10:00-10:15</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Introduction of Cluster Meeting Strategies- a how to session with handouts and Morning Break</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>10:15-11:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>403, 404A, 404B, 405A, 405B, Catalpha, 412</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session I:</strong> In small groups, attendees will explore and discuss current topics, and then select one for which the group will develop (in session 2) interventions, strategies, and resources for sharing with Saturday’s attendees.  Guidelines will be distributed.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>11:00-11:55</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Union Ballroom</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IIA</strong><strong></strong>\r\n\r\nPart 1 (11:00 - 11:25)\r\n\"It’s All About Location: Reflections on Student Preparedness and the Transfer of Knowledge\"\r\nDr. Chris Anson</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Plenary Session IIB</strong><strong></strong>\r\n\r\nPart 2 (11:25 - 11:55)\r\nTeaching Writing in the 21st Century: Question and Answer Open Session with Dr. Chris Anson</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Noon-1:00</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Lunch</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"4\"><strong>1:00-2:15</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>403</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Catalpha</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop\r\n</strong>Teaching Grammar in the Context of Student Writing\r\nFacilitated by Ellen Shelton &amp; Anna Britt-Begnaud</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop</strong>\r\nBeyond the MLA: Strategies for teaching style guide use\r\nFacilitated by Alice Myatt &amp; Ruth Mirtz</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>405A</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>404A</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop\r\n</strong>Identifying the role of technology in the composition classroom\r\nFacilitated by Mike Schwartz, Kathleen Turner &amp; Andrew Davis</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Idea Exchange</strong>\r\n<strong>Workshop</strong>\r\nIntegrating peer response in the writing classroom\r\nFacilitated by Paula Miller &amp; Amber Jensen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>2:15-3:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>403, 404A, 404B, 405A, 405B, Catalpha, 412</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session II:</strong> Building on Cluster Session I, groups will continue strategizing, intervening, and sharing resources .</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>3:30-3:45</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Cluster Session Recap:</strong> Each group will select a presenter who will deliver the results of the cluster session to the attendees from 11:00-Noon on Saturday. Presentations may be made via the Internet (Transitioning website), PowerPoint, Prezi, handouts, giant poster-pad notes, or a combination of the preceding. Resources, including laptops and access to a printer, will be made available as needed. Contact Andrew Davis or Joanne Mitchell to arrange for access to resources.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>3:45-4:00</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Break: Prep for Tours</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>4:00-5:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Walk of Champions</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>J.D Williams Library</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 1</strong>\r\nDouble Decker Bus Tour of UM campus and Oxford with Dr. Andy Mullins</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 2\r\n</strong>Writing Center - Main Campus with Alice Myatt</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Tour Option 3\r\n</strong>Archives and Special Collections with Leigh McWhite</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>5:15-6:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Ole Miss Oxford Depot</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Viewing at the Depot\r\n</strong>Reception with snacks and sodas provided.\r\nWriting Assessment and Responding to Student Writing: View and Discuss the videos <em>Beyond the Red Ink</em> and <em>Writing Across Borders</em>.\r\nFacilitated by Sheena Boran &amp; Kathleen Turner</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<table id=\"table-3\" width=\"100%\" border=\"5\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-1\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"5\"><strong>Saturday, September 29, 2012</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>7:30-8:30</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Buffet Style Breakfast</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>8:30-8:45</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Welcome\r\n</strong>Dr. Ellen Shelton, National Writing Project<strong></strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\"><strong>Opening Remarks</strong>\r\nDr. Stephen Monroe, Associate Dean, College of Liberal Arts</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>8:45-9:30</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"><strong>Plenary Session IIIA\r\n</strong>“Standards to Teach By: The Common Core &amp; the Framework for Success in Postsecondary Writing Standards and How They Affect Teaching Writing at All Levels”- Dr. Ellen Shelton with Karen Forgette (University of Mississippi)</td>\r\n<td colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\" width=\"40%\"><strong>Plenary Session IIIB\r\n</strong>“Building Bridges for Transition: Supporting Writing Classrooms with Writing Centers” (A Resource Tool Kit)- Dr. Kerri Jordan, Mississippi College, and Amber Jensen, Edison High School. Followed by a question and answer session.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>9:30-9:45</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Break</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"4\"><strong>9:45-11:00</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room A\r\n</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room B\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion</strong>\r\nClosing the divide between expectation and reality in the writing classroom\r\nFacilitated by Guy Krueger &amp; Sheena Boran</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion\r\n</strong>Writing in the Disciplines: Strategies for the writing classroom, Presentation by Angela Green\r\nFacilitated by Andrew Davis and Alice Myatt</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Seminar Room C\r\n</em></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion\r\n</strong>Dual-enrollment courses and first-year composition\r\nFacilitated by Deborah Kehoe, Anna Britt-Begnaud, Victoria Bryan, &amp; Robert Cummings</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"2\" valign=\"top\"><strong>Roundtable Discussion</strong>\r\nIntegrating peer response into the writing classroom and writing center\r\nFacilitated by Keith Boran, Paula Miller &amp; Amber Jensen</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" rowspan=\"2\"><strong>11:00-Noon</strong></td>\r\n<td class=\"td-2\" style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><em>Yerby Auditorium\r\n</em></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\" colspan=\"4\"><strong>Group Presentations of Interventions:</strong>\r\nA representative from each cluster will deliver a presentation based on their group work</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Noon-1:30</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan=\"4\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: center\"><strong>Lunch and Closing Session\r\nViewing of selected <em>Take 20</em> clips\r\nPlanning for 2013 - </strong>announcements and dates to save</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', 'Events', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1156-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-16 16:00:37', '2014-09-16 16:00:37', '', 1156, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/1156-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(1175, 1, '2014-09-17 13:42:14', '2014-09-17 13:42:14', '<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_0834.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright wp-image-160 size-medium\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_0834-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"2011 Breakout Session\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>Since 2011, I’ve been privileged to work with, meet, and learn from dedicated and forward-thinking writing teachers from throughout Mississippi. Regardless of their particular designation or teaching location, they want to engage their students in learning how to become better writers and effective communicators. They are excited by opportunities to expand their awareness of how they can best support students who will transition from writing in one setting to another, usually unfamiliar, setting, knowing that many of their students will experience such transitions several times as they progress in their academic and/or professional work. Such teachers respond to the challenge of educating students to be able competitors in today’s global marketplace, and they enrich the sessions, workshops, and roundtables offered each year at our annual Transitioning to College Writing symposia. Thus, our theme for this year’s symposium is an apt one: “Global Connections, Local Partnerships: Writing across Borders in a Digital Age.” The theme speaks to global connections we enjoy as well as local partnerships that have enriched our teaching across public and private secondary and post-secondary settings, and it responds to our long-standing interest in how writing and composing work in digital environments around the world.\r\n\r\nThis year, our symposium responds to suggestions from past attendees and our current planning committee. We continue with our tradition of bringing visiting scholars to the symposium, and we have expanded our inclusion of Mississippi-based scholars who speak to our particular locales of writing instruction. Join us on Friday, October 10 and Saturday, October 11, as we learn from and respond to Mr. Vinnie Segalini, Director of English Language Arts with the Mississippi Department of Education, Dr. Lawrence T. Potter, Professor of English at Jackson State University, and Dr. Frances di Lauro of the University of Sydney in Sydney, Australia. Topics range from supporting secondary-school teachers as they implement the Common Core State Standards, to understanding how writing becomes an effective tool for student transitions by means of reflective practice; to integrate writing into other content areas by means of writing across the curriculum strategies; to using digital writing tools and helping students become more literate digital citizens.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_0849.jpg\"><img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-165\" src=\"http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/IMG_0849-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"Teachers at the Transitioning Symposium \" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></a>We continue to focus on the value of integrating writing centers in secondary and post-secondary Mississippi schools. In 2011, when the first Transitioning to College Writing planning committee convened, we wanted to include someone who could represent a high school writing center. We did not find any, but we had (fortuitously) tapped into a deep interest in incorporating writing centers in secondary school settings. That first year, then, we brought Amber Jensen, a high school English teacher from Edison High School in Virginia, to share with us her experiences in setting up a writing center at her high school, especially since she’d done that with very limited resources. 2011 attendees also heard from Anna Britt Begnaud, who was (and still is) the writing center director at Itawamba Community College here in Mississippi. Both Amber and Anna are returning as visiting speakers at this year’s symposium, and as I write this post, I’m thrilled to know that there are now several secondary writing centers here in Mississippi that, guided by tested scholarship on writing center studies, are supporting student writers in various ways. Students who have access to such writing centers are experiencing – before they enter college or begin their careers – the value of talking about their writing projects with others, of understanding the role of authentic audiences as they write, and they are aided to write with purpose and careful attention to supporting their writing with evidence-based claims and persuasion.\r\n\r\nOver the next three weeks, visit this Blog page often to read posts from our program planners. We’ll also continue to post about specific workshops and events that will take place during the symposium. Learn more about our visiting speakers and the topics they will be speaking on by selecting the Speakers tab on this website. Many secondary and post-secondary teachers will be leading workshops, guiding roundtable conversations, and sharing resources that we can use when we return back to our local writing landscapes. Review the program schedule, register for the Symposium, and we hope to see you here in Oxford soon!\r\n\r\n– Alice Johnston Myatt, Department of Writing and Rhetoric, University of Mississippi', 'Welcome to the 2014 Transitioning to College Writing Symposium', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1171-revision-v1', '', '', '2014-09-17 13:42:14', '2014-09-17 13:42:14', '', 1171, 'http://transitioning.olemiss.edu/1171-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
